          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825861?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> SAG-Aftra members hold a rally in Times Square in New York, July 25.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Cindy Ord/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Sorry, Peggy Noonan, but this reader could easily survive a prolonged Hollywood strike (“ <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-talent-strikes-back-hollywood-union-writers-actors-tv-movie-industry-6bf4e49f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">The Talent Strikes Back</a> ,” Declarations, July 22).</p><p> I don&#39;t need Hollywood to live and prosper. No more tiresome action movies and sequels, woke themes, awards extravaganzas that fewer people watch and articles about “stars” cluttering the news?没问题。</p><p> My hope is the strike ends in the entire industry&#39;s demise and rebirth. Regardless, I will get by.</p><p> <strong>Gerald Katz</strong></p><p> <em>Edwards, Colo.</em></p><p> Ms. Noonan makes the Hollywood writers and actors strike understandable to us lay folks. Which brings me to the ultimate solution: Have all the old movies from the 1940s through the 1970s brought back on as many TV channels as possible. It will introduce several generations to what real movie-making was about.</p><p> Younger viewers would have a taste of great acting, in appropriate dress, and superb writing. Unlike the dreck on streaming and TV services today. If viewers come to reject bad stuff, Hollywood just might produce higher-quality products. And by the way, for us senior citizens, start showing these movies well before 9 pm</p><p> <strong>Steven H. Berliner</strong></p><p> <em>Elon, NC</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 21:13:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="fals